review_comments.body:
The interface assumes the configuration object, and the souces that are added, are implementing the same contract. In the end they won't.

We should consider changing the namespace, or changing the class to be called Settings. The app does know the difference between a single config and a collection and there's no reason to make it look like the two layers are fungible.

```
var conf = new Configuration();
conf.AddIniFile("app.ini");
conf.Add(new CustomSource());
conf.AddOverrides(new Dictionary<string,string>() {
  {"Foo:Bar", "forty-two"}
});
```

Methods to add particular sources should be extension methods and return the collection class.

```
var conf = new Configuration()
  .AddIniFile("app.ini")
  .Add(new CustomSource())
  .AddOverrides(new Dictionary<string,string>() {
    {"Foo:Bar", "forty-two"}
  });
```

To be honest, I'd even be okay dropping the "Add" from the ext method name, but I'm sure we'll want to keep the verb-centricity.

